{ Before the start of the last round of the 2020 Russian Championship, Ian Nepomniachtchi and Sergey Karjakin were sharing the lead with 7 out of 10. Nepo made a quick draw against Maxim Chigaev and all eyes were now on the game between Daniil Dubov and Sergey Karjakin. Would Dubov be able to create any chances against Karjakin, the 'Minister of Defence'?  Dubov played amasterpiece that many will remember for the spectacular queen sacrifice on move 19. Karjakin had just played 18... Be6 and now Dubov played the 'move of the year' 19. Qxg6!!  Dubov sacrifices his queen for two minor pieces, a passed pawn, and a menacing attack on Black's king. Karjakin resigned on move 38, which handed Nepomniachtchi the 2020 Russian Championship title.  Few people will remember the novel opening that Dubov used to create these chances. It was the first time that this opening was used at the highest level and another example of the creative and inspiring play of Dubov.  The subject of this course is the position that arises after the moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. b4
{ Dubov suggested to his coach Sasha Riazantsev that this would be an amusing line for a blitz game. His coach took it to the next level and provided some deep analysis that made it suitable for over-the-board play at the highest level. Dubov's assessment of the variation is:  'All in all, the line looks decent for White; I don't see a way for Black to get an advantage, which is quite something for such a sharp position.'  The goal of the opening is to pursue dynamic, unbalanced positions where Black is under immediate pressure. White often sacrifices a pawn in exchange for an attack, an advanced passed pawn, more space, and a lead in development. The main lines are quite forced and thus better preparation and a better understanding of the imbalances, in combination with superior calculation will win you the game.  For this mini-course I used the article Dubov's Challenge by IM Yuriy Krykun in New In Chess Yearbook 138  (2021)   and the analysis by Daniil Dubov of his game against Sergey Karjakin for New In Chess Magazine 2021 #1. In addition, I consulted the Hiarcs Openings Book, the Lichess games database, the ChessBase Mega Database, and Correspondence Database, and engine analysis  (Stockfish 14, Leela Chess Zero, and Komodo Dragon 2)  .  I selected and prioritized theChapter 2. Variations based on the Lichess games database  (online games, both rapid and classical, across all ratings)  . The course was created with club players in mind. The first variation in the mini-course is the variation that you are most likely to get! The mini-course includes typical mistakes of club players and shows how to refute them. I deliberately kept the book small  (about 15 variations)  . It is enough for me, as a titled player, to play the opening with confidence over the board and has proven sufficient to beat 2400+ players online.   I often give the Stockfish 14 evaluation of a certain position. For many club players, it is hard to gauge how big an advantage is when the material is equal. My recommendation is that when Stockfish evaluates a position as significantly better and you don't understand why that you open an Analysis Board in Chessable and play a few human moves for the Black side to see how play develops. This way you get a feel of how to build an attack against a vulnerable king, how to cash in a passed pawn or how to exploit a badly placed piece.  Chapter 3. Puzzles is meant to reinforce key motifs and tactical themes. You have to find the best move: sometimes it is a tactic and sometimes it is the strongest move. The number of stars * in front of the puzzle indicates the difficulty of the puzzle.   I appreciate any questions or feedback you might have. They will only help make the mini-course only clearer and better!  The mini-course is complimentary to my Evans Gambit - Beginner's Guide and Scotch Gambit - Modern Attack - Beginner's Guide. The course is a great alternative to the Evans Gambit with many of the same themes as in the Evans Gambit and the Scotch Gambit. }
