{ This section provides information on general opening principles and the first moves of Dubov's Giuoco Forte.   As a trainer in the Steps Method I teach my students the following basic opening principles  (3 Golden Rules)  :      Pawns in the centre  The pawns provide space and support for your own pieces and limit the activity of your opponent's pieces.     Develop your pieces  Develop your pieces towards the middle of the board where they can be as active as possible and support the pawns in controlling the centre. Good cooperation between the pieces adds to the overall activity of your pieces. Develop your knights and bishops first and, in general, the queen last. The queen is the most valuable piece and you can lose time when she gets chased by minor pieces.    Bring your king into safety  The king is vulnerable in the middle of the board and can come easily under attack on the e-file or through an attack on the vulnerable squares f2 and f7. A castled king is much safer. 
  Complete your development by bringing all your pieces into the game. Find a good square for your queen and connect your rooks.  The side that completes his opening most effectively can start attacking first.   A good metaphor to use for your pieces is an 'army'. During your game constantly ask yourself: Is my next move adding maximum energy to my forces? Are all soldiers engaged? Are they working well together? Are any team members vulnerable?   These are guiding principles. Under the influence of chess engines, play has become more concrete. Opening principles can be violated in specific circumstances based on concrete analysis with 3,600 rated engines. }
1. e4
{ The pawn on e4 controls d5 and f5  (important squares on the opponent's half of the board that Black can no longer occupy with his pieces)  .   After 1. e4, the bishop on f1 and the queen on d1 can enter the game. }
1... e5
{ The most popular moves after 1.e4 are 1... e5  (42%)  , 1... c5  (25%)  and 1... e6  (11%)  .   1... e5 is the symmetrical response leading to less immediate tension and combat than 1... c5  (Sicilian)  . After 1.e4, White threatens to play 2.d4, which would give White a strong grip of the centre. Both 1... e5 and 1... c5 prevent White from controlling the centre with 2 pawns. }
2. Nf3
{ Developing the knight towards the centre and attacking the pawn on e5. } 2...
Nc6
{ With this move, Black protects the pawn on  e5  . Please note that if Black chooses  2...Nf6  to maintain the symmetry, he will never reach complete equality because White will always have the first-move advantage and at a certain moment Black will not be able to continue to copy White's moves, for instance in the case of a check. }
3. Bc4
{ 3. Bb5 @@StartBracket@@Ruy Lopez@@EndBracket@@ was by far the most popular choice of masters. This started to change after Kramnik used the Ruy Lopez - Berlin Defence to defeat Kasparov in the World Championship match in 2000 and was reinforced by analysis with the strongest engines in recent years.   3.Bb5  Nf6  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  The queens are off, Black has the bishop pair and White has a better pawn structure. Practice has shown this to be very solid for Black.   The Marshall Attack is the second reason why White players have switched from 3.Bb5 to 3.Bc4  3.Bb5  a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.O-O  Be7  6.Re1  b5  7.Bb3  O-O  8.c3  d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6=∞  Black will continue Bd6-Qh4 and often Bg4-Rae8-f5 and Black's attack and active bishop pair compensate for the one pawn deficit. }
3... Bc5
{ The main alternative is  3...Nf6  on which I recommend:  4.d4  exd4  5.e5  See my course the Scotch Gambit - Modern Attack.   The main alternative for 4. d4 is 4. Ng5  3...Nf6  4.Ng5  d5  5.exd5  Na5  6.Bb5+  c6  7.dxc6  bxc6  8.Bd3  Nd5  9.Nf3  Bd6  Black's pawn structure might be damaged and Na5 out of play, but I never liked playing against the piece activity of Black.   Some players choose for 4. Ng5 just hoping that their opponent blunders into the so-called Fried Liver Attack  3...Nf6  4.Ng5  d5  5.exd5  Nxd5?  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qf3+  Ke6  8.Nc3  Ncb4  9.O-O  c6  11.d4  Nxc2  12.dxe5  Nxa1  13.Rd1+- }
4. c3
{ White wants to occupy the centre with d4 and take back with a pawn on d4 after exd4.   After  4.b4  we enter the Evans Gambit, an opening on which I also wrote amini-course. This opening was successfully played in classical games by world champions Kasparov, Fischer, Morphy and lesser Gods like Nakamura and Short. White sacrifices material in exchange for a lead in development and more space often leading to an attack on Black's king.  4...Bxb4  5.c3  Ba5  6.d4  exd4  7.O-O    The understanding of the trade-off between material, development and space is critical in chess. When players start out playing chess, they are often focused on the material balance only. They keep score using the values: pawn =1; knight=3; bishop=3, rook=5 and queen= 9 to 10 with a bonus for the bishop pair of 0.5. These values depend a lot on the activity of the piece. Kasparov taught us that a stable knight on the 6th rank, a so-called Octopus, is worth at least a rook.   At the start of this introduction, I suggested using army as a metaphor for your chess pieces. It is not surprising that with more space and a lead in development your army is more active and thus more forceful.  Kaufman concluded that if White has two extra moves at the start of the game @@StartBracket@@e4 and d4@@EndBracket@@ that Black is lost! So after 1.e4 Nc6 2. d4 Nb8, Black can already resign! Material is equal but Black lacks space and is behind in development. This also implies that Black has to be very careful not to waste any time in developing his pieces. }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues to develop, Nf6 attacks the pawn on e4 and Black is now ready to castle and bring his king into safety. He allows the move d4 by White as Black will counter with d5 shortly thereafter.   The move  4...d6?!  gives White the centre he is aiming for after  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+   Or  6...Bb6  7.Bb5  Bd7  8.Nc3  White controls the centre and is slightly better.  7.Nc3  Bg4  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Nd5+-  White threatens Bg5, pinning Nf6 and threatening to destroy Black's pawn structure, and after  9...Nxd5  10.exd5  Ne7  Black loses Bb4 after  11.Qa4  with a double attack on Ke8 and Bb4.   Even worse is  4...h6?  5.b4  Bb6  6.b5  Na5  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Nxe5+  and White has a winning advantage. }
5. d4
{ By playing this move White now attacks the Bishop on  c5  and the pawn on  e5  . On the other hand, this move does not protect the undefended pawn on  e4  .  Top players prefer  5.d3  d6  6.O-O  O-O  followed by Nb1-d2-f1-g3 with the idea of occupying f5 and attacking the Black king. 5. d4 is considered too direct to gain an advantage because of the line given after 6. cxd4. See below. }
5... exd4
{ 5...Bd6  is the only way to protect the pawn on e5 but is a bad move: Black has difficulty completing his development, Bd6 has very limited activity. Stockfish 14 evaluates this position already as +2. }
6. b4
{ There are 1.2 million games in the Lichess database with 3... Bc5. Only 2,200 feature 6. b4!? i.e. 0.2% or 1 in 500 games. This opening has a strong surprise factor and the lines are very poisonous!  White puts Black under immediate pressure by attacking Black's bishop and will subsequently attack Nf6 with the pawn advance e4-e5. White's play is logical and easy to memorize.  Most frequently, Black retreats his bishop to b6 after which Bg5 attacking Qd8 becomes a theme.     In the mainline  6...Bb6  7.e5  d5  8.exf6  dxc4  9.Qe2  Be6  10.b5  Na5  11.fxg7  , White gets an advanced passed pawn on  g7  .  White aims to secure his pawn with Bg5-f6 and Bg5 also prevents Black's king from castling long. Black's king is often subject to a direct attack.     The most popular move played by White on move 6 is  6.cxd4  Bb4+  7.Bd2  Bxd2+  8.Nbxd2  d5!  Black does not allow White to keep his centre majority  9.exd5  Nxd5  with equality. }
