{ Before we go into the woods of the variations, let's spend one moment to look at this line from Black's perspective. Instead of looking 'inside-out', we will be looking 'outside-in'! Dubov's Giuoco Forte is a rarely played variation so which line will Black likely use as his reference? }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5
{ This is the start of the Giuoco Piano - Anderssen variation.  It was used from time to time by Evgeny Sveshnikov and most recently by Wesley So. Let's compare the position with the mainline of the Dubov's Giuoco Forte after 7. e5.    Giuoco Piano - Anderssen variation     Dubov's Giuoco Forte   We have the same position with the moves b4 and Bb6 inserted in the mainline of Dubov's Giuoco Forte.  What are the main differences  (the variations are replayable further below)  :  1. In the Giuoco Piano, Black's knight is trapped after 6... Ne4 7. Bd5.  In Dubov's Giuoco Forte, Black can save his knight by taking on c3. 6. b4 Bb6 7. e5 Ne4 8. Bd5 Nxc3    2. The insertion of the move b4 makes Ra1 more vulnerable to a potential attack with Bd4, which is an important factor after 6... Ng4.   In the Giuoco Piano Black's is much worse after 6... Ng4 7. cxd4 and White controls the center and threatens h3-Nh6-Bxh6.  In Dubov's Giuoco Forte, Black can play 6. b4 Bb6 7. e5 Ng4 8. 8.cxd4?! Nxd4! 9.Nxd4 d5 10.Be2 Nxf2 11.Kxf2 Qh4+ 12.g3 Qxd4+ 13.Qxd4 Bxd4+ and Black wins.  With the pawn on b2, Ra1 would not be under attack.  3. In Dubov's Giuoco Forte, White can play b5 chasing the knight on c6. The knight on c6 controls the crucial squares d4 and e5. This makes in the Dubov's Giuoco Forte the variation 8. exf6 dxc4 9. Qe2+ Be6 10. b5 Na5 11. fxg7 Rg8 12. Nxd4 feasible.   In the standard Giuoco Piano this line is not possible as Nc6 controls d4.    Replayable Dubov's Giuoco Forte variations:   6.b4  Bb6  7.e5  d5   7...Ne4  8.Bd5  Nxc3  9.Nxc3  dxc3   7...Ng4  8.cxd4?!  Nxd4!  9.Nxd4  d5  10.Be2?  Nxf2-+  11.Kxf2  Qh4+  12.g3  Qxd4+  13.Qxd4  Bxd4+-+  8.exf6  dxc4  9.Qe2+  Be6  10.b5  Na5  11.fxg7  Rg8  12.Nxd4  threatening Nxe6. Most Black players take twice on  d4  , but that allows White to activate his bishop to  b2  and protect the pawn on  g7  .  In the Giuoco Piano the only good reply against 6. e5 is 6... d5. It does not come as a surprise that in  Dubov's Giuoco Forte ,  7... d5 is by far the most popular choice by Black. }
6... d5
{ 6...Ne4  7.Bd5  Trapping the knight.  7...Nxf2  8.Kxf2  dxc3+  9.Kg3  cxb2  10.Bxb2±  Black has 3 pawns for a piece and White's king is unsafe, but this is not enough. White will play h3-Kh2 bringing his king into safety and use his active piece to attack the Black king. SF14:+2   6...Ng4  7.cxd4  Bb4+   7...Nxd4?!  8.Nxd4  d5  9.Be2  Nxf2  10.Kxf2  Qh4+  11.g3  Qxd4+  12.Qxd4  Bxd4+  13.Kg2±  Bd4 is not attacking Ra1 as the pawn is still on  b2  .  8.Nc3+-  White is much better SF14:+3. After  8...d5  White maintains the tension with  9.Bb5  . The knight on  g4  is vulnerable and White threatens to damage Black's pawn structure after h3-Nh6-Bxh6 }
7. Bb5
{ 7.exf6  dxc4  and Black is better as White is missing the b4-b5 push to destabilize Nc6.  8.Qe2  Be6  9.fxg7  Rg8  SF14:-4 White does not have Nxd4 as Nc6 is protecting  d4  . }
7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ The Anderssen-variation is  8...Bb4+  9.Bd2  Nxd2  10.Nbxd2  O-O  with a slight pull for White. Most recently only the move 8... Bb6 is being played by top GMs.   The comparison between the standard Giuoco Piano and Dubov's Giuoco Forte has taught us that most Black players will choose for 6... Bb6 and 7... d5 as these are the best replies in the standard Giuoco Piano.  This is confirmed by the games in the Lichess database with the move 6... Bb6 being the choice in 78% of the games after 6. b4, and 7... d5 being the choice in 45% of the games after 7. e5. }
