{ There are 1.2 million games in the Lichess database with 3... Bc5. Only 2,200 feature 6. b4!? i.e. 0.2% or 1 in 500 games. This opening has a strong surprise factor and the lines are very poisonous! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ 4...d6?!  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+   6...Bb6  7.Bb5  Bd7  8.Nc3  White controls the centre and is slightly better.  7.Nc3  Bg4  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Nd5+-  White threatens Bg5, pinning Nf6 and threatening to destroy Black's pawn structure, and after  9...Nxd5  10.exd5  Ne7  Black loses Bb4 after  11.Qa4  with a double attack on Ke8 and Bb4.   4...h6?  5.b4  Bb6  6.b5  Na5  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Nxe5+  and White wins. }
5. d4 exd4 6. b4
{ White puts Black under immediate pressure by attacking Black's bishop and will subsequently attack Nf6 by the pawn advance e4-e5. White's play is logical and easy to memorize.  Most frequently, Black retreats his bishop to b6 after which Bg5 attacking Qd8 becomes an important theme. }
6... Bb6
{ The move 6... Bb6 is played in 78% of the games with 6... Be7 a distant second at 14%. The remaining 8% are for clearly worse moves, like 6... Bd6 and 6... Nxb4.     6...Bd6?  7.O-O  O-O  8.b5  Na5  9.Bd3±  White threatens e4-e5 forking Bd6 and Nf6. It is hard for Black to complete his development.   6...Nxb4?  Black gets three pawns for a knight but it is not enough. White has a huge lead in development and is the first to attack.  7.cxb4  Bxb4+  8.Bd2  Bxd2+  9.Nbxd2  c5  10.O-O  O-O  11.Qb3  d6  12.e5  SF14:+3  When the bishop retreats to e7, the disadvantage for Black is that the bishop is less active than on b6 and not fighting for the control of the centre. The advantage is that the move protects the h4-d8 diagonal  (White can not attack Qd8 with Bg5)  . Black claims that White overextended himself with the pawn pushes b5 and e5 and Be7 can get quickly back into the game.   After  6...Be7  7.e5  the moves  7...Ng4  and  7...Ne4  are equally popular.   6...Be7  7.e5  Ng4  8.cxd4  Bxb4  9.Bd2  Bxd2  10.Qxd2  is a solid line for Black.  'White's centre seems rather impressive, but he is a pawn down and Black is about to undermine the centre with d7-d6. However, the g4-knight is very misplaced and White is more active at the moment. I think that after a sequence of careful moves the position peters out into equality.' IM Yurily Krykun, New In Chess YearBook 138 - 2021   6...Be7  7.e5  Ne4  8.b5  Na5  9.Bd3  Nxc3  10.Nxc3  dxc3  11.Qa4  b6  12.O-O  with equality. Note that Black can not castle immediately as  12...O-O  fails to the double attack  13.Qe4  attacking both Ra8 and h7. White will continue to exert pressure with Qe4 or Qg4. }
7. e5
{ White asks Black the next question: How to defend Nf6 against e5? Black's options are a counterattack in the centre  (d5)  , move away  (Ne4 or Ng4)  or pinning the attacker  (Qe7)  .  Most played are now:  7... d5  45% 7... Ne4 20% 7... Ng4 17% 7... Qe7 13%   (Lichess Rapid and Classical - all ratings) }
7... d5
{ 7...Ne4  Karjakin's choice  8.Bd5  Nxc3  9.Nxc3  dxc3  10.Bg5  Ne7  11.O-O  O-O?!   Castling short is played most frequently but better is  11...h6  12.Bh4  g5  13.Nxg5  hxg5  14.Bxg5  d6  15.Qf3  Be6  16.Bxb7  Rb8  17.Bc6+  Kf8  18.Rad1=∞  12.Bb3  h6  13.Qd3!  this is the point, Black can not take on g5 because of:  13...hxg5  14.Nxg5  Ng6  15.Qxg6+-  with mate on h7 to follow.     After  7...Ng4  8.O-O  White has three threats:  Bg5 attacking Qd8  Damaging Black's pawns structure with h3-Nh6-Bxh6 A pin with Re1 if Black opens the e-file with Ngxe5 or d6   An example of the first threat:  8...dxc3  9.Bg5  Ne7  10.Nxc3+-  and the threat of Nd5 attacking the pinned Ne7 is lethal.     An example of the second threat:  7...Ng4  8.O-O  O-O  9.cxd4  d5  10.Bb3  Nxb4?!  11.h3  Nh6  12.Bxh6  gxh6±  Black's pawn structure in front of his king has been damaged and White will attack the vulnerable king.   7...Qe7?  This is just a one-trick pony. After White castles, the pin is gone and White threatens again to take on f6. In addition, the queen has no squares to go to after Bg5 and will be pinned when the e-file opens up.  8.O-O  Ng4   8...Nxe5  9.Nxe5  Qxe5  10.Re1  Ne4  11.Nd2  d5  12.Bxd5  Qxd5  13.c4  Qf5  14.Nxe4+-  9.Bg5+-  f6  10.exf6  gxf6  11.Re1+-  pinning Qe7. }
8. exf6 dxc4 9. Qe2+ Be6
{ 9...Kf8?  10.b5  d3  11.Qe4  Na5  12.Qe5  and White is winning. After  12...Qxf6  13.Ba3+  Black has to give up his queen to avoid mate on e8. In addition, White is threatening 13. fxg7+ and Black gets mated after  12...gxf6  13.Bh6+  Kg8  14.Qg3+ }
10. b5
{ White asks Black a third question: How to defend against bxc6? Black's main options are: d3  (counterattack on the queen)  and Na5 or Nb4  (moving away)  . }
10... d3
{ A natural reaction  (played in 72% of the games after 10. b5)  to secure the passed pawn and create a threat on the queen. But this move activates the queen after she moves to e4, from where the queen also eyes h7. Better is 10... Na5  (played in 17% of the games)  or the rarely played 10... Nb4  (Anand's choice)  .     10...Na5  played in 17% of the games  11.fxg7  Rg8  12.Nxd4  Bxd4  13.cxd4  Qxd4?  This gives White the opportunity to activate his bishop, protect pawn g7 and prevent Black from castling after Bb2-Bf6.   Better  13...Rxg7  14.O-O  Qd5  15.g3  O-O-O  16.Nc3  Qxd4  17.Rd1  Qxc3  18.Rxd8+  Kxd8  19.Bb2  Qb4  20.Bxg7  Qxb5  21.Qe4=  14.Bb2  Qd3  15.Bf6!  Preventing Black from castling long. Taking the Qd3 would give the badly placed knight on a5 the square c4. See mymodel game - SF14:+3   10...Nb4  is played in 2% of the games after 10. b5 and was the choice of Viswanathan Anand in hisgame against chess sponsor Oleg Skvortsov in the Zürich Chess Challenge. Black sacrifices a piece for two passed pawns and an active bishop pair. The resulting position is very unbalanced. I recommend the following continuation  11.cxb4  Qxf6  12.O-O  O-O  13.a4 }
11. Qe4 { Black's knight on c6 is still under attack and has to move now. }
11... Na5 12. fxg7 Rg8 13. Bg5
{ To prevent Black from castling long and to prepare Bf6, protecting the pawn on g7.   The immediate  13.Qxh7?  is worse as Black is OK after  13...f6  14.O-O  Qd7  15.Bh6  O-O-O }
13... Qd5 14. Qxh7 { Do not trade pieces when you are attacking. } 14... Kd7
15. O-O
{ Note the lack of space of the Black king and queen. To illustrate the threat, imagine White could play two moves in this position: Re1-Ne5+ The Black king can not go to the back rank because of Qxg8 and has to move to d6 where it can be attacked by Bg5-f4 of by Nbd2-e4.   The Black queen also just has the square d6 if White is allowed to play after Re1-Re5.   In addition, Na5 is still out of play and Rg8 is occupied with preventing the promotion of pawn g7.    The following line highlights the weakness of e5 and f6 if Black tries to untangle himself with natural moves   15...Rae8  to connect the rooks and prepare Kc8  16.Nbd2  Kc8  17.Rae1  Qxb5  to allow the knight to come back into the game via Na5-Nc6.  18.Re5  Qd7  19.Ne4  SF14: +8!  Stockfish 14 evaluates the position after 15.O-O as +3 for White. }
